<DOC><DOCNO> AP880319-0075 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 1100EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-UN-NicaraguaVisit     03-19 0233</FIRST><SECOND>PM-UN-Nicaragua Visit,0240</SECOND><HEAD>U.N. Observer Mission Heading To Nicaragua</HEAD><DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A team of U.N. observers will visitNicaragua as soon as possible to investigate the tense bordersituation with Honduras, a U.N. spokesman said Saturday.   Mahbub Ahmad said Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellardecided to send the team at Nicaragua's request. He said it wouldinclude one poliitical officer from U.N. headquarters and astill-undecided number of military observers.   Diplomatic sources said the team was likely to inclkude twomilitary observers and probably would leave Tuesday. The observershave not been named.   The announcement followed a Security Council meeting Fridaynight during which Nicaragua, Honduras and the United States tradedallegations over whether Sandinista troops are in Honduranterritory and who is responsible for the current conflict.   Several Latin American speakers endorsed Nicaragua's call for aneutral U.N. observer mission to visit the site of the borderclashes.   Ahmad said there are no immediate plans to visit the Honduranside of the border. Sources said no request had come from Honduras.   Nicaragua has requested a joint mission by the U.N. and theOrganization of American States to investigate the border situationand make recommendasntions on preventing further conflict.   Honduras and the United States contend that Nicarguan troopshave attacked Contra bases in Honduras. Nicaragua has denied theclaim.   Honduras has responded by attacking Nicaraguan forces around theborder area.</TEXT></DOC>